programme.desc: On this week's episode of Midwest Whitetail, we join Mike Reed on the new property that he's teased. Much like the infamous River Farm, the makeup of the dirt is heavily WRP. With this in mind, Mike kicks things off by deep diving on WRP. Covering what exactly it is, how a property owner could obtain WRP, and the advantages/disadvantages it offers for recreational use. With plenty of lessons learned over the years with the River Farm, Mike moves through the new property applying his 5 part process to break down a new spot for year one success. Through this process, Mike introduces multiple key spots, talks about how he identified them, and breaks down how he expects them to pay off this year. Finally, stick around until the very end of the video to see a first hand look at a great buck Mike filmed that he has history with.

programme.title: Food Plots Anyone Can Do, A Full Breakdown On Cost Saving Methods
programme.desc: On this week's episode of Midwest Whitetail, we're building off of last week's episode where we covered food plot 101 from top to bottom. Now on this video, we're covering a full breakdown on cost saving methods for food plots anyone can do. We cover why these methods are great for hunting, where and what to look for when selecting locations, and how to go about bringing your idea to life. To kick things off, Josh Sparks breaks down a poor man style plot he just recently finished transforming on a permission property that he hopes will offer another edge in filling a tag this season on one of two awesome bucks. Then we join Zach Rozmus who for years has utilized the "poor man" strategy to have food to hunt. Going into depth on everything you need to know, our goal is to layout where to start and how to execute the plan to create the food plot anyone can do. From there, we wrap things up with Rye Ludwig on a permission property he calls the Otter Farm. With a year of hunting the property under his belt, Rye breaks down how he's using past stand observations, trail camera intel, and more to carve out a spot that he believes will make his hunting even better.

programme.title: E4: First Buck Ever In Missouri, Droptine Buck Appears

Mike Reed sits the River Farm and has a great drop tine buck appear in front of his stand. Gavin Koterba takes a shot at a great buck on his permission property. Owen Reigler and Devin Wills take another swing in the stand overlooking the rub post. Zach Rozmus discusses the number one buck for his hunting season. Rounding it out, Mike and Rye Ludwig fill 3 doe tags with the archery equipment continuing to chip away at their goal.
